# AI-Driven Development Guardrails

## Purpose

Additional guardrails for AI agents implementing code in the bridle project.
This rule supplements `v5_bridle.mdc` with safety measures specific to AI-driven development.

For the full command workflow (main direct vs PR flow), see `@.cursor/README.md`.

## Container Prerequisite

All R commands run inside the Podman container `bridle-dev`.
Before any R-related work:

1. Verify the container is running: `make doctor`
2. If not running: `make container-up`
3. If first time: `make container-build && make container-up && make renv-init`

## Pre-Implementation Checks (Required)

Before writing any code:

1. **Run `make doctor`** to verify the development environment
2. **Read relevant ADR(s)** from `docs/adr/` for the feature being implemented
3. **Read relevant schema(s)** from `docs/schemas/` if the change touches data structures
4. **Check existing patterns** in `R/` to maintain consistency (see Phase-Aware Guidelines below)

## Phase-Aware Guidelines

### First implementation (R/ is empty or has very few files)

- YAML schemas (`docs/schemas/`) and ADRs (`docs/adr/`) are the primary references.
- Create the first S7 class following ADR-0001 strictly.
- Establish naming/style conventions that subsequent code will follow.
- Use `scaffold-class` command to generate boilerplate from schemas.

### After initial classes exist

- Check existing patterns in `R/` for consistency before adding new code.
- Follow established naming conventions, error handling patterns, and documentation style.

## Type Strictness (S7)

- All S7 properties **MUST** have explicit types. `class_any` is **prohibited** unless the property genuinely accepts multiple unrelated types with no common interface.
- Use `S7::new_union(class_character, class_integer)` for known union types rather than falling back to `class_any`.
- Validators must check constraints that types alone cannot express (e.g., value ranges, cross-field dependencies, format patterns).
- Use `match.arg()` for enum-like parameters.

## Schema-Code Consistency (Critical)

YAML schemas (`docs/schemas/`) and S7 classes (`R/`) must remain consistent.
Per ADR-0001, S7 classes are the source of truth once implemented.

- When creating/modifying an S7 class, verify it matches the corresponding YAML schema
- When modifying a schema, update the corresponding S7 class (or create a follow-up task)
- Run `make validate-schemas` after any schema-related change

## Mandatory Verification After Changes

After every implementation:

1. `make ci-fast` (minimum: schema validation + lint)
2. `make test` (if tests exist for the changed area)
3. `make check` (before commit)
4. `make document` (if roxygen2 tags were added or changed)

## Change Safety Checklist

For every PR/commit, verify:

- [ ] ADR reference identified (or "no ADR applies" stated)
- [ ] Schema-code consistency maintained
- [ ] No prohibited patterns introduced (see `@.cursor/rules/quality-check.mdc`)
- [ ] S7 properties have explicit types (no `class_any`)
- [ ] Tests added/updated for new functionality
- [ ] `make ci` passes locally

## Multi-Agent Coordination

When multiple AI agents work concurrently:

- Use task prefixes (see `@.cursor/rules/debug.mdc` Section 0) for all artifacts
- Check `git status` before starting work to detect concurrent changes
- Keep changes scoped to minimize merge conflicts
- Do not modify the same file from multiple agents simultaneously

## Makefile Quick Reference

| Target | Purpose | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `make doctor` | Environment health check | Before starting work |
| `make ci-fast` | Schema validation + lint | After implementation |
| `make ci` | Full local CI | Before commit |
| `make test` | Run tests | After implementation |
| `make check` | R CMD check | Before commit |
| `make check-fast` | Quick R CMD check | During iteration |
| `make validate-schemas` | YAML schema check | After schema changes |
| `make document` | Regenerate NAMESPACE/man | After roxygen2 changes |
| `make format` | Auto-format with styler | Before lint |
| `make changed-lint` | Lint changed files only | During iteration |
| `make changed-test` | Test changed areas only | During iteration |
| `make scaffold-test` | Create test skeleton | When adding tests |
